pan": {"begin": 287, "end": 289}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:28938"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "N4", "obj": "drug", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 291, "end": 293}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:29372"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "O2", "obj": "drug", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 299, "end": 301}}, {"id": ["mesh:D003596"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cytosine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9985804557800293, "span": {"begin": 315, "end": 323}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:36825"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "N3", "obj": "drug", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 333, "end": 335}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:29372"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "O2", "obj": "drug", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 337, "end": 339}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:46442"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "O4", "obj": "drug", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 345, "end": 347}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013941"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "thymine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9875878691673279, "span": {"begin": 361, "end": 368}}, {"id": ["mesh:D001564"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "benzo(a)pyrene", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9996742010116577, "span": {"begin": 604, "end": 618}}, {"id": ["mesh:C012293"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "N7", "obj": "drug", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 654, "end": 656}}, {"id": ["mesh:D011687"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "purines", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.8607199788093567, "span": {"begin": 667, "end": 674}}, {"id": ["mesh:C000228"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Aristolochic Acid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999527096748352, "span": {"begin": 690, "end": 707}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000225"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "adenine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9896689057350159, "span": {"begin": 731, "end": 738}}, {"id": ["mesh:D016604"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Aflatoxin B1", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9998059868812561, "span": {"begin": 743, "end": 755}}, {"id": ["mesh:D006147"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Guanine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.6871376633644104, "span": {"begin": 783, "end": 790}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "chromosome", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.4866742789745331, "span": {"begin": 947, "end": 957}}], "text": "Bulky DNA adducts are formed when activated genotoxic aromatic compounds interact with the nitrogenous bases of DNA. This occurs at various sites. The most common reactive sites for these adduct is C8, N7, N3 and N2 positions of guanine, the N7, N6, N3, and N1 positions of adenine, the N3, N4, and O2 positions of cytosine, and the N3, O2, and O4 positions of thymine (As reviewed by Hwa Yun et al., 2020). The position of the adduct depends on the chemical structure of the activated aromatic compound. Some adducts are not stable, but some can persist. For example, the most harmful adducts formed by benzo(a)pyrene are from radicals that bind to the N7 and C8 of purines (IARC., 2012). Aristolochic Acid forms adducts at N6 of adenine and Aflatoxin B1 forms adducts at the N7 of Guanine (Arlt et al., 2002). This KE describes an increase in Bulky adducts. These adducts can cause depurination, transversions which in turn cause DNA damage and chromosome aberrations.", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:23:11 +0000 2026"}